<subSubSection pageId="13" pageNumber="325" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="13.[816,1429,523,1356]" box="[816,955,523,549]" pageId="13" pageNumber="325">
<emphasis box="[816,955,523,549]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="325">Description</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="13.[816,1429,523,1356]" pageId="13" pageNumber="325">
A medium-small bat but with a greatly shortened forearm (
<quantity box="[928,1041,590,616]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.02" pageId="13" pageNumber="325" unit="mm" value="30.2">30.2 mm</quantity>
) (
<tableCitation box="[1067,1161,590,616]" captionStart="TABLE" captionStartId="7.[159,172,220,241]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="TABLE 2. External measurements (mm) and bacular length (mm) of 14 bat species recently collected at Lekoumou, Congo.Acronyms explained in the Materials and Methods section include means, ranges, and, where relevant, standard deviations. Numbers in parentheses refer to sample size where they differ from those stated in column 2" httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/5FAA6645FF93C07DFF03FF23FC6EFEEE" pageId="13" pageNumber="325" tableUuid="5FAA6645FF93C07DFF03FF23FC6EFEEE">Table 2</tableCitation>
) and a reduced wing; the phalanges of third, fourth and fifth digits are all excessively short. The fur is extremely short and together with the wings, interfemoral membrane, ears and face is dark brown throughout. The inner margin of each ear is considerably thickened; the tragus has a very short anterior border, a broadly rounded tip and a longer posterior border (
<figureCitation box="[1254,1356,826,852]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="11.[159,172,1911,1932]" captionTargetBox="[287,1299,1270,1885]" captionTargetId="figure@11.[211,1406,1263,1892]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIG. 8. Right tragus of (A): Glauconycteris alboguttata, HZM.1.40172, ♀; (B): G. beatrix, HZM.1.40181, ♀; (C): Hypsugo crassulus, HZM.1.40190, ♂; (D): Neoromicia brunnea, HZM.1.40191, ♂; (E): N. nana, HZM.321.40186, ♂; (F): N. tenuipinnis, HZM.7.40170, ♀; (G): Pipistrellus nanulus, HZM.1.40189, ♂; (H): Mimetillus moloneyi, HZM.10.40177, ♂; (I): Miniopterus inflatus, HZM.19.40182, ♂. Scale = 2 mm" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3943579" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3943579/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="325">Fig. 8H</figureCitation>
). The skull, which has a greatest length of 
<quantity box="[1302,1429,859,885]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.419" pageId="13" pageNumber="325" unit="mm" value="14.19">14.19 mm</quantity>
(
<tableCitation box="[824,920,893,919]" captionStart="TABLE" captionStartId="8.[99,112,725,746]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="TABLE 3. Cranial and dental measurements (mm) of 14 bat species recently collected at Lekoumou, Congo.Acronyms explained in the Materials and Methods section include means, ranges, and, where relevant,standard deviations. Numbers in parentheses refer to sample size where they differ from those stated in column 2" httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/5FAA6645FF9CC072FFFFFD2AFAA7FCC7" pageId="13" pageNumber="325" tableUuid="5FAA6645FF9CC072FFFFFD2AFAA7FCC7">Table 3</tableCitation>
) is characteristically broad and flattened with a broad flat rostrum, a broad flat braincase and a well-developed supraorbital tubercle on each side (damaged in the specimen illustrated in 
<figureCitation captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="14.[159,172,1911,1932]" captionTargetBox="[344,1217,713,1874]" captionTargetId="figure@14.[304,1284,688,1902]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIG. 10. Skulls of three small vespertilionids, including lateral view of right upper incisors and occlusal view of left mandibular dentition (left) and left maxillary dentition (right) of (A): Hypsugo crassulus, HZM.1.40190, ♂; (B): Mimetillus moloneyi, HZM.10.40177, ♂ and (C) Pipistrellus nanulus, HZM.1.40189, ♂. Scales for skulls and occlusal views of toothrows (left and right) = 2 mm; scale for upper incisors (centre) = 1 mm" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3943583" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3943583/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="325">Fig. 10B</figureCitation>
). The first upper incisor (I 
<superScript attach="right" box="[1202,1212,1023,1041]" fontSize="8" pageId="13" pageNumber="325">2</superScript>
) is small and bicuspid; the second (I 
<superScript attach="left" box="[1087,1097,1057,1075]" fontSize="8" pageId="13" pageNumber="325">3</superScript>
) is about half the height of I 
<superScript attach="left" box="[867,877,1090,1108]" fontSize="8" pageId="13" pageNumber="325">2</superScript>
and unicuspid (
<figureCitation box="[1091,1207,1095,1121]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="14.[159,172,1911,1932]" captionTargetBox="[344,1217,713,1874]" captionTargetId="figure@14.[304,1284,688,1902]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIG. 10. Skulls of three small vespertilionids, including lateral view of right upper incisors and occlusal view of left mandibular dentition (left) and left maxillary dentition (right) of (A): Hypsugo crassulus, HZM.1.40190, ♂; (B): Mimetillus moloneyi, HZM.10.40177, ♂ and (C) Pipistrellus nanulus, HZM.1.40189, ♂. Scales for skulls and occlusal views of toothrows (left and right) = 2 mm; scale for upper incisors (centre) = 1 mm" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3943583" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3943583/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="325">Fig. 10B</figureCitation>
). The upper premolar (P 
<superScript attach="left" box="[917,927,1124,1142]" fontSize="8" pageId="13" pageNumber="325">4</superScript>
) is less than half the crown area of the first molar (M 
<superScript attach="left" box="[935,945,1158,1176]" fontSize="8" pageId="13" pageNumber="325">1</superScript>
) (
<figureCitation box="[978,1093,1162,1188]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="14.[159,172,1911,1932]" captionTargetBox="[344,1217,713,1874]" captionTargetId="figure@14.[304,1284,688,1902]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIG. 10. Skulls of three small vespertilionids, including lateral view of right upper incisors and occlusal view of left mandibular dentition (left) and left maxillary dentition (right) of (A): Hypsugo crassulus, HZM.1.40190, ♂; (B): Mimetillus moloneyi, HZM.10.40177, ♂ and (C) Pipistrellus nanulus, HZM.1.40189, ♂. Scales for skulls and occlusal views of toothrows (left and right) = 2 mm; scale for upper incisors (centre) = 1 mm" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3943583" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3943583/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="325">Fig. 10B</figureCitation>
). The first lower premolar (P 
<subScript attach="left" box="[842,852,1210,1228]" fontSize="8" pageId="13" pageNumber="325">2</subScript>
) is minute, about half the crown area of the second (P 
<subScript attach="left" box="[934,944,1244,1262]" fontSize="8" pageId="13" pageNumber="325">4</subScript>
). Despite dissecting the penis, no baculum was found; this agrees with 
<bibRefCitation author="Hill and Harrison" firstAuthor="Hill" pageId="13" pageNumber="325" pagination="225 - 305" refId="ref14024" refString="HILL, J. E., and D. L. HARRISON. 1987. The baculum in the Vespertilioninae (Chiroptera: Vespertilionidae) with a systematic review, a synopsis of Pipistrellus and Eptesicus, and the description of a new genus and subgenus. Bulletin of the British Museum (Natural History), Zoology, 52: 225 - 305." type="journal article" year="1987">Hill and Harrison (1987: 237)</bibRefCitation>
who also reported the absence of a baculum.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="13" pageNumber="325" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="13.[816,1429,1398,1558]" box="[816,1014,1398,1424]" pageId="13" pageNumber="325">
<emphasis box="[816,1014,1398,1424]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="325">Taxonomic notes</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="13.[816,1429,1398,1558]" pageId="13" pageNumber="325">
This specimen from 
<collectingCountry box="[1127,1205,1431,1457]" name="Democratic Republic of the Congo" pageId="13" pageNumber="325">Congo</collectingCountry>
is here assigned to the nominate race (see 
<bibRefCitation author="Simmons" box="[1124,1310,1465,1491]" firstAuthor="Simmons" pageId="13" pageNumber="325" refId="ref14567" refString="SIMMONS, N. B. 2005. Order Chiroptera. Pp. 312 - 529, in Mammals species of the World (D. E. WILSON and D. M. REEDER, eds). Johns Hopkins University Press, Baltimore, 2142 pp." type="book" year="2005">Simmons, 2005</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="Happold and Happold" firstAuthor="Happold" pageId="13" pageNumber="325" refId="ref13898" refString="HAPPOLD, M., and D. C. D. HAPPOLD (eds.). 2013. Mammals of Africa Volume IV: Hedgehogs, shrews, and bats. Bloomsbury Publishing, London, 800 pp." type="book" year="2013">Happold and Happold, 2013</bibRefCitation>
for further comments on the taxon).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
